# Text cleaning 
import re

def clean_text(text):
    
    text = text.lower()
    text = re.sub(r'[^a-z\s]', '', text)
    
    text = re.sub(r'i recommend this product', '', text)
    text = re.sub(r'i dont recommend this product', '', text)
    text = re.sub(r'this review was collected as part of a promotion', '', text, flags=re.IGNORECASE)   # Removed specific phrases
    
    return text

# Applying text cleaning to 'review_description' and 'recommended review'
gamestop['cleaned_review_description'] = gamestop['review_description'].apply(clean_text)
gamestop['cleaned_recommended_review'] = gamestop['recommended_review'].apply(clean_text)
gamestop['cleaned_review_title'] = gamestop['review_title'].apply(clean_text)

In [56]:
sia = SentimentIntensityAnalyzer()

# Function to get compound sentiment score
def get_sentiment_score(text):
    return sia.polarity_scores(text)['compound']

gamestop['sentiment_score'] = gamestop['cleaned_review_title'].apply(get_sentiment_score)
gamestop['sentiment'] = gamestop['sentiment_score'].apply(lambda x: 'Positive' if x > 0 else 'Negative' if x < 0 else 'Neutral')
sns.set(style="whitegrid")

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
sns.countplot(x='sentiment', data=gamestop, palette='coolwarm')
plt.title('Sentiment Distribution', fontsize=16, fontweight='bold')
plt.xlabel('Sentiment', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('Count', fontsize=12)
plt.xticks(fontsize=10)
plt.yticks(fontsize=10)
plt.grid(axis='y', linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)

# Show plot
plt.show()

from nltk.tokenize import word_tokenize
from nltk.corpus import stopwords
from nltk.probability import FreqDist
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def get_most_frequent_words(text, top_n=20):
    words = word_tokenize(text)
    words = [word.lower() for word in words if word.isalpha() and word not in stopwords.words('english')]
    word_freq = FreqDist(words)
    return word_freq.most_common(top_n)

positive_reviews_text = ' '.join(gamestop[gamestop['sentiment'] == 'Positive']['cleaned_review_title'])  # Get positive reviews
negative_reviews_text = ' '.join(gamestop[gamestop['sentiment'] == 'Negative']['cleaned_review_title'])  # Get negative reviews based on sentiment categorization

most_frequent_positive_words = get_most_frequent_words(positive_reviews_text)
most_frequent_negative_words = get_most_frequent_words(negative_reviews_text) # To get the most frequent words for positive and negative sentiments

filtered_positive_words = [(word, freq) for word, freq in most_frequent_positive_words if word not in ["product", "batteries", "monitor", "game"]]
filtered_negative_words = [(word, freq) for word, freq in most_frequent_negative_words if word not in ["good", "fun", "headset", "great", "rig", "hs", "game"]]

# Plot the word frequency distributions
fig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 1, figsize=(12, 12))
axes[0].bar(*zip(*filtered_positive_words), color='green')
axes[0].set_title('Most Frequent Positive Words (Filtered)')
axes[0].set_xlabel('Words')
axes[0].set_ylabel('Frequency')
axes[1].bar(*zip(*filtered_negative_words), color='salmon')
axes[1].set_title('Most Frequent Negative Words (Filtered)')
axes[1].set_xlabel('Words')
axes[1].set_ylabel('Frequency')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

#Converting the column reviewed_at to date format
def convert_to_timedelta(value):
    if 'year' in value:
        return timedelta(days=int(value.split()[0]) * 365)
    elif 'month' in value:
        return timedelta(days=int(value.split()[0]) * 30)
    elif 'day' in value:
        return timedelta(days=int(value.split()[0]))
    elif 'hour' in value:
        return timedelta(hours=int(value.split()[0]))
    else:
        raise ValueError("Unsupported time unit")

# Convert 'reviewed_at' to timedelta
gamestop['timedelta'] = gamestop['reviewed_at'].apply(convert_to_timedelta)

# Define today's date
today_date = datetime(2022, 1, 1)

# Convert timedelta to date by subtracting from today's date
gamestop['review_date'] = today_date - gamestop['timedelta']

# Display the resulting DataFrame
print(gamestop[['reviewed_at', 'review_date']])

Word Cloud of Positive and Negative Words¶

In [37]:
def get_most_frequent_words(text, top_n=20):
    words = word_tokenize(text)
    words = [word.lower() for word in words if word.isalpha() and word not in stopwords.words('english')]
    word_freq = FreqDist(words)
    return word_freq.most_common(top_n)

# Get positive reviews
positive_reviews_text = ' '.join(gamestop[gamestop['sentiment'] == 'Positive']['cleaned_review_title'])

# Get negative reviews based on sentiment categorization
negative_reviews_text = ' '.join(gamestop[gamestop['sentiment'] == 'Negative']['cleaned_review_title'])

# Get the top 20 most frequent words for positive and negative sentiments
top_20_positive_words = get_most_frequent_words(positive_reviews_text, top_n=20)
top_20_negative_words = get_most_frequent_words(negative_reviews_text, top_n=20)

# Filter out specific words from positive and negative words
filtered_positive_words = [word for word, freq in top_20_positive_words if word not in ["product", "monitor", "game"]]
filtered_negative_words = [word for word, freq in top_20_negative_words if word not in ["good", "great", "rig", "hs", "game"]]

# Generate larger word clouds
wordcloud_positive = WordCloud(width=1000, height=600, background_color='white').generate(' '.join(filtered_positive_words))
wordcloud_negative = WordCloud(width=1000, height=600, background_color='white').generate(' '.join(filtered_negative_words))

# Plot the larger word clouds
plt.figure(figsize=(20, 12))

plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
plt.imshow(wordcloud_positive, interpolation='bilinear')
plt.title('Word Cloud for Top 20 Positive Words')
plt.axis('off')

plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
plt.imshow(wordcloud_negative, interpolation='bilinear')
plt.title('Word Cloud for Top 20 Negative Words')
plt.axis('off')

plt.show()

def preprocess(text):
    tokens = word_tokenize(text)
    tokens = [word.lower() for word in tokens if word.isalpha() and word not in stopwords.words('english')]
    return tokens

# Apply preprocessing to your cleaned_review_description
gamestop['tokens'] = gamestop['cleaned_review_description'].apply(preprocess)
